A Bombus hypnorum is a species of bumblebee commonly found in Europe and parts of Asia.
It has a yellow and black fuzzy body with a distinctive ginger thorax, giving it a unique appearance.
The wings are transparent and have a slight tint of brown, which is more noticeable when viewed up close.
The legs are hairy and have black spurs, which help it grip onto flowers and plants.
It is typically found in gardens, meadows, and woods where it feeds on nectar and pollen from a variety of flowering plants.
Unlike other bumblebees, Bombus hypnorum can nest in small cavities such as bird boxes, making it a popular subject for research in urban ecology.
Overall, Bombus hypnorum is an important pollinator that helps maintain the fragile balance of ecosystems.
